				<note resp="Philip Lampi">John C. Wright was elected, but resigned the seat on March 3, 1821, the day before the start of the 17th U.S. Congress.</note>
				<note resp="Philip Lampi">The official votes (minus the rejected votes from Monroe township) were John C. Wright with 4682 votes and David Chambers with 4659, giving John C. Wright a majority of 23 votes.   Western Herald and Steubenville Gazette (Steubenville, OH).  November 11, 1820.</note>
				<note resp="Philip Lampi">"One township in Morgan, which probably voted unanimously for Col. Chambers failed to make a return."  Muskingum Messenger (Zanesville, OH).  October 24, 1820.</note>
				<note resp="Philip Lampi">"In 1818 the townships of Freeport, Nottingham and Stock, in Harrison County, made returns of votes for a member of Congress in the fourth congressional district to the clerk of Harrison, and they were rejected by the examining officers, because they were not within the district.  In October, 1820, these same three townships, together with two others called Rock and North, one third part of each of which latter townships also lay within the limits of the sixth congressional district, made returns of votes for a member of Congress in the fourth district, to the same clerk of Harrison county, and were examined by one of the same justices who opened the polls in 1818, and they were received, and certified to the Secretary of State.  These five townships gave Mr. Wright 350 votes and Mr. Chambers 15 votes - and as these votes on a contest will necessarily be subtracted from the polls of each party, the legal votes of each would then probably stand thus - Chambers 4683, Wright 4326, Majority for Chambers, 357."  Muskingum Messenger (Zanesville, OH).  November 7, 1820.</note>
